<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0128 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1234EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Satellite     03-08 0170</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Satellite,0176</SECOND><HEAD>China Successfully Launches 22nd Satellite</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   China has successfully launched into orbit its22nd satellite, a synchronous communications satellite, it wasreported Tuesday.   The nationally televised evening news showed a Long March 3rocket blasting off Monday night from a launch site in Xichuang,Sichuan province.   Acting Premier Li Peng, who was shown with military leaderswatching the launch of the telecommunications satellite, latercongratulated scientists and technicians on its success.   The Long March 3 is China's most sophisticated rocket.   Reports have said the three-stage rocket's launch capabilitieswere nearly doubled last year, and it can now put a payload of 2{tons into geosynchronous orbit 22,320 miles above Earth.   China launched its first satellite in 1970 and has recovered all10 of the retrievable satellites it put into space.   It began offering launch services for foreign countries lastyear. Two U.S. companies have contracted with China to launchcommunications satellites this year. China also is to put aNorwegian satellite into orbit in 1991.</TEXT></DOC>